## V:tM-SPECIFIC SAFETY PHRASES

### **[STAINS-OFF]**

*"Pause the Humanity-loss bookkeeping for this scene."*

Sometimes a scene needs to be played for character exploration without the 
weight of Humanity-mechanic consequences. [Stains-Off] tells the AI to 
narrate the scene as character work without applying mechanical Stains 
afterward.

Example:
> *"My character is going to do something monstrous in this scene because 
> I want to explore it. [Stains-Off] for this beat — I want the writing, 
> not the mechanical consequence."*

### **[VEIL]**

*"This content needs to happen but should be off-screen."*

Mid-scene tool. When the player invokes [Veil], the current content 
transitions to narrated rather than depicted form. The scene continues; 
the camera moves.

Example:
> *Mid-feeding scene: "[Veil] — yes she feeds on him, yes it's intense, 
> the scene moves to her leaving the alley afterward."*

### **[SLOW]**

*"Slow down — I need more interiority and less plot velocity."*

V:tM is a personal-horror genre and sometimes the AI moves too fast through 
emotionally weighty content. [Slow] tells the AI to give a moment more 
room — more interior monologue, more environmental detail, more space 
between beats.

### **[FAST]**

*"Speed up — too much density, get to the next beat."*

The opposite. Used when a scene is bogged in detail that isn't serving the 
chronicle.

### **[CONSULT]**

*"Pause. I want to discuss the chronicle direction OOC."*

A flag for an OOC conversation about where things are going, what plot 
beats are coming, whether the chronicle is still serving the player. The 
AI steps out of character and engages directly.

### **[ANCHOR]**

*"Bring me back to my Touchstones / Convictions / mortal life."*

A scene-redirection tool for when the chronicle has been monstrous-heavy 
for a while and the player wants to ground in the human relationships that 
anchor the character. The AI engineers a scene of contact with a Touchstone, 
or a return to mortal-grounded life.

### **[DARK]**

*"Take this fully into the genre's darkness — I'm consenting to intensity."*

The opposite of safety phrases. [Dark] tells the AI the player WANTS the 
scene to go to its full intensity — the genre's intended weight without 
restraint. Used by players who specifically want personal-horror content 
at full register and have prepared themselves to receive it.

### **[FAITH]**

*"Engage with the genre's faith / spiritual / metaphysical content seriously."*

V:tM has significant Catholic / metaphysical / spiritual content — True 
Faith, Golconda, the wraiths of the dead, the question of damnation. 
[Faith] tells the AI the player wants this content engaged with rather 
than skirted around.

### **[MORTAL-PRIORITY]**

*"Center the mortal characters in this scene."*

V:tM is structurally about Kindred but its emotional weight often lives in 
mortal characters (Touchstones, family, the unaware). [Mortal-Priority] 
tells the AI to give a mortal NPC the scene's attention — their interiority, 
their reactions, their reality.

